<article>
    <h1>New be&#xAD;gin&#xAD;nings</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201018/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-10-18"><time>2020-10-18</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE | FOOD &amp; DRINK</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>Two chefs who left their Miche­lin-starred es­tab­lish­ments are all set for new ven­tures.</p>
    <p>Chef Ja­son Tan, for­merly of one-Miche­lin-starred Cor­ner House at Botanic Gar­dens, will open Restau­rant Eu­pho­ria in Tras Street by the end of the month.</p>
    <p>It will show­case an “evolved and el­e­vated ver­sion” of his sig­na­ture gastro-botan­ica cui­sine, such as his fa­mous Cevennes onion dish.</p>
    <p>Chef Man­ju­nath Mu­ral, from the now-de­funct The Song Of In­dia restau­rant, is com­menc­ing ren­o­va­tions on his new In­dian restau­rant Adda.</p>
    <p>The 2,000 sq ft space – ad­ja­cent to night­club Magic Car­pet in Beach Road – is slated to open by the end of next month and will of­fer his take on mod­ern In­dian cui­sine along with spice-based cock­tails.</p>
    <p>He is al­ready sell­ing mithai (In­dian sweets) on­line for the up­com­ing Deep­avali cel­e­bra­tions.</p>
    <p>On go­ing ca­sual and of­fer­ing what he calls “fun din­ing”, the 47-year-old chef says: “In an­other two years, the econ­omy will back­slide and fine din­ing will be af­fected. Ca­sual din­ing will do well as peo­ple be­come price con­scious.”</p>
    <p>Over at 104 Amoy Street, chef Christophe Ler­ouy’s new lo­ca­tion is set to open in the mid­dle of next month. His epony­mous one-Miche­lin-starred French restau­rant closed its Stan­ley Street lo­ca­tion last Thurs­day af­ter three years. The 25-seat Ler­ouy is al­ready fully booked for its open­ing week.</p>
    <p>An­other highly an­tic­i­pated open­ing to round off the year is two-Miche­lin-starred Waku Ghin by Tet­suya Wakuda.</p>
    <p>A Ma­rina Bay Sands spokesman says it will re­open in a new space on the same floor as its former lo­ca­tion in the last quar­ter of this year.</p>

